<span class="header1">NATURE</span>
<p>If you enjoy nature or are concerned about the environment, this occupational field may be for you.  People who work in this field enjoy life sciences and understand business.</p>

<hr size="1" />

	<span class="header2">Life Science Museum Director</span><br /><br />
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>If you enjoy helping others know about the environment and nature, you might become a life science museum director.  In this job, you would plan and oversee the daily routine of a museum. You would manage employees and keep the building in good repair. Most directors start out as a museum curator.  Later, they are promoted the director's job.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
	<blockquote>You must have a Master's Degree to become a museum director. Many directors have their Ph.D.  Employers look for directors who have plenty of experience in the museum business.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>The yearly salary ranges from $20,000 to $100,000+.</blockquote>

<hr size="1" />

	<span class="header2">Wildlife Manager</span><br /><br />
	<img class="job_pic" src="/images/icons/CH/1270.jpg" width="100" height="100" border="0" alt="Wildlife Manager" />
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>Wildlife managers look for ways to protect wild animals and their habitats.  As a wildlife manager, you would do more than look after the well-being of individual animals.  You would care for their homes as well.  You would monitor the plants, water, and soil of the area to be sure they could sustain the animals.  If you found a problem, you would work to solve it.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
	<blockquote>Competition for these jobs is intense.  You need at least a Master's Degree. The more education and experience you have in caring for wild animals and their habitats, the more likely you are to get a job. Your leisure activities and part-time jobs can help you to gain experience.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>Wildlife managers earn between $21,000 to $80,000 a year.</blockquote>

<hr size="1" />

	<span class="header2">Grass Roots Coordinator</span><br /><br />
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>A grass roots coordinator oversees the activities of a group of people who are working to protect or restore the environment.  As a grass roots coordinator, you might work for a national organization,  but you would live and work in a county or town. You would help protect the environment or animals in the wild. To do this job well, you must feel strongly about protecting the environment.  You must also be able to motivate people to work toward your cause.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
	<blockquote>There are no formal requirements to become a grass roots coordinator, but there are some college-level courses that are valuable, inluding business,communications, biological sciences, and political science. What is most important is that you have a strong commitment to the environmental cause that you coordinate.  You must also have the knowledge needed to do the job.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>Many coordinators have another job. The yearly salary is very low.</blockquote>

